general.text:
This is the lecturer’s drunken entrance, and the line is funny because it is both pitiful and theatrical. Instead of beginning with a proper formal address, he produces a half-collapsed call to the audience: “Peo-ple!.. Ah… ay-oo!” It sounds like someone trying to gather himself into public oratory and failing immediately.

The humor comes from several things at once:
- the collapse of the expected lecture register at the very first moment;
- the physical comedy encoded in the broken vocalization;
- the contrast between public-speaking ambition and drunken helplessness;
- the fact that this is still recognizably an attempt to address a crowd.

The stretched, broken shape matters. It is not just “Люди!” but a faltering, wavering cry. The sound pattern carries part of the joke: he is already losing control of speech before he has said anything meaningful.

Translation risk:
If this is normalized into a clean “People!” or “Ladies and gentlemen!”, the drunken physical comedy disappears. The line needs to remain vocally unstable, like an attempted formal opening that immediately dissolves into slurred or wandering sound.

The humor here comes from watching a man who is in no state to give a lecture but is trying to produce something lecture-like. The beginning is already funny because it is absurdly weak as scientific content: “we can see two little stars, three little stars, four little stars…” This sounds like a childish or silly counting sequence, not like meaningful astronomy. It is pseudo-explanation without substance.

Then the punchline suddenly snaps into place: «Лучше всего, конечно, пять звёздочек!» That is funny because, after a pointless one-two-three buildup, the final item becomes meaningful — but meaningful in a completely different frame. The phrase clearly belongs to the cognac star system, not to astronomy. So the line lands as a drunken derailment: he has tried to stay inside the lecture topic, but his mind has wandered off into the logic of what he has been drinking.

That is why the moment works so well:
- the “lecture” begins as empty, silly counting;
- the final step suddenly becomes culturally legible;
- but it is legible in the wrong domain;
- the result is both absurd and festive, because the failed lecture accidentally turns into good entertainment.

It also fits the film’s broader structure very well: the official lecture slot, which should have been the deadest part of the evening, becomes a success precisely because it collapses into nonsense and joins the holiday mood instead of resisting it.

Translation risk:
The counting progression should sound trivial and slightly ridiculous, not informative. The final “five stars” must feel like a sudden click into a different semantic world. If that shift is lost, the line becomes merely odd instead of hilariously derailed.

This is one of the film’s most famous lines, and part of the joke is that the lecturer is not actually wrong. At the time, science really did not know whether there was life on Mars. So the humor does not come from factual absurdity, but from the way a genuinely unresolved scientific question is phrased by a drunken lecturer in language that is far too casual, loose, and unscientific for the setting.

That is what makes the line memorable:
- the topic is real and perfectly legitimate for a lecture;
- the answer is also basically correct;
- but the wording reduces scientific uncertainty to colloquial everyday speech;
- “science” is treated almost like a person who simply has not yet been briefed.

The key comic effect lies in the register mismatch. «Это науке неизвестно» is already flatter and less grand than one expects from public scientific speech, and «Наука ещё пока не в курсе дела» is even more strikingly conversational. The line sounds as if a major cosmic problem is being explained in the language of ordinary practical awareness.

That is why the audience can enjoy it on two levels at once:
- as a funny failure of lecture style;
- as an unexpectedly accurate summary of the actual state of knowledge.

It also fits the festive mood of the film very well: the official lecture slot becomes enjoyable not because it delivers serious enlightenment, but because real science, drunken looseness, and accidental comic phrasing briefly coincide.

Translation risk:
The line should not be made too pompous or too formally scientific. The content is valid, but the comic force lies in the casual phrasing of that valid uncertainty. The target version should preserve both sides at once: factual correctness and stylistic inappropriateness.
